To create a TikZ diagram that represents the local situation around the \(i\)-th self-intersection of a curve \(\gamma\) with the numbers \(k = 1, \ldots, 8\) in red, you can use the following TikZ code:

```latex
\documentclass{standalone}
\usepackage{tikz}

\begin{document}
\begin{tikzpicture}[scale=2]
    % Draw the circle representing the neighborhood around the intersection point
    \draw[thick] (0,0) circle (2);

    % Mark the intersection point
    \fill (0,0) circle (2pt) node[above right] {$i$};

    % Draw the tangents at the intersection point
    \draw[->, thick] (-2,-2) -- (2,2) node[midway, above left] {$T_1$};
    \draw[->, thick] (2,-2) -- (-2,2) node[midway, below right] {$T_2$};

    % Label the points k=1,...,8 in red
    \foreach \x in {1,...,8} {
        \pgfmathsetmacro{\angle}{360/\x * (\x - 1)}
        \node[red, rotate=\angle] at ({cos(\angle)}, {sin(\angle)}) {\x};
    }
\end{tikzpicture}
\end{document}
```

This code will generate a TikZ diagram showing a circle representing the neighborhood around the \(i\)-th self-intersection point. The intersection point is marked with a filled dot labeled \(i\). Two tangents \(T_1\) and \(T_2\) are drawn from the intersection point to represent the directions of the tangents at the intersection. The numbers \(k = 1, \ldots, 8\) are placed evenly around the circle in red.

You can compile this code using a LaTeX editor that supports TikZ, such as Overleaf, TeXShop, or any other LaTeX editor of your choice.

